A team of biologists led by the Wildlife Conservation Society in New York identified a new species of boss dolphin off the northern coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, Head of Scientific Mission to the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Marine Animals and Milieus (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new species of bough dolphin surprise you?
That's good news, but I'm not particularly surprised.
While in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomical and geographical basis, today the development of new tools such as genetics allows us to improve our knowledge in species classification sciences.
It is not impossible for these advances in genetics and molecular biology to question the classification or belonging of a species to a genus, family or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are called into question because of advances in genetics.
Likewise, two very close species morphologically have been distinguished through genetics.
This is the case of the new species that has just been identified.
About ten years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: the Pacific Boss dolphins and Atlantic Boss whales.
Recent analyses have identified four species.
Why is this an important discovery as claimed by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
If this population had been known for a long time by researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this area.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a viral epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could have a case of extinction of a species, rather than a local disappearance of a population of a more widely spread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered endangered or threatened by the number of individuals existing on Earth, i.e. stock, and the possibility of recovery from nearby stocks.
As for the species Sousa chinensis, whose population of the new discovered species has emerged, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogenous, open habitats, where there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene blend limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
It must be known that the marine environment is the least well known environment.
We prefer to send robots to Mars, rather than to know what lives in the Mariannes pit, only 11 kilometres from the sea surface.
We spend more money on the quest for life on other planets than on marine research and it's high time that it changes.
